In this paper, we provide a novel method designed to handle missing values in datasets: the Gaussian Copula Imputation Framework (GCIF). To simulate real-world situations where partial records may be obtained during data gathering, we purposefully added randomly occurring NaN (Not a Number) values into the datasets utilized in our study. Imputing these missing values is important because it protects the validity and consistency of the analysis and interpretations that come after. To fill in these data gaps, we use a variety of imputation approaches such as MissForest, KMM Imputer, Simple Imputer, Iterative Imputer, and the suggested Gaussian Copula Model. We prove the superiority of the Gaussian Copula based imputation approach by evaluating the Kolmogorov-Smirnov metric and adversarial validation scores over different percentages of NaN values. Our results highlight the significance of strong
